{{Notability|biography|date=April 2017}} '''Anthony J. Lisska''' is [[Maria Theresa Barney|Maria Theresa Barney professor of philosophy]] at [[Denison University]], Granville, Ohio. He is a specialist in [[Analytical Thomism|Thomism and analytic philosophy]] and the thinking of [[St. Thomas Aquinas]]. He describes his "intellectual avocation" as [[regional history]] and he has written several books on the [[history of Ohio]].<ref>[http://denison.edu/people/anthony-lisska Tony J. Lisska.] [[Denison University]]. Retrieved 21 October 2016.</ref> In 2016, the [[Denison University]] Gilpatrick Center was rededicated as the Lisska Center for Scholarly Engagement in honor of Anthony Lisska and his contributions to the university.<ref>https://denison.edu/academics/research/the-lisska-center-for-scholarly-engagement [[Denison University]]. Retrieved 9 November 2017.</ref><ref>http://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2016/05/11/scholarly-engagement-center-named-lisska/84133984/</ref> These contributions include serving as dean, chairing the philosophy department, and founding and chairing the Honors Program.
==Selected publications== *''Philosophy matters''. Charles Merrill, 1978. *''Aquinas theory of natural law: An analytic reconstruction''. [[Oxford University Press]], Oxford, 1996. *''A history of Aquinas College High School'' *''An illustrated history of the Buckeye Lake Yacht Club''. 2007.
